  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/70159098" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1381999-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1361847236p2/1381999.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/70159098?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/1381999-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1381999-david?shelf=childrens-materials">childrens-materials</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer70159098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6047617498914279357">Can we say overrated? This is supposed to be one of the greatest classics in Children&apos;s Literature, and the winner of the Newbery in 1986. There&apos;s no character development...no action...just a bunch of waiting around for some kind of story to develop.<br/><br/>I can summarize this story with these questions and answers coming from the snot-nosed, little children in the novel: &quot;Will we have a mother? Will Sarah come? Will she like me? Will she stay? Yes.&quot; <br/><br/>Boring. Thank God Glenn Close made the character so</span>
  <span id="freeText6047617498914279357" style="display:none">Can we say overrated? This is supposed to be one of the greatest classics in Children's Literature, and the winner of the Newbery in 1986. There's no character development...no action...just a bunch of waiting around for some kind of story to develop.<br /><br />I can summarize this story with these questions and answers coming from the snot-nosed, little children in the novel: "Will we have a mother? Will Sarah come? Will she like me? Will she stay? Yes." <br /><br />Boring. Thank God Glenn Close made the character somewhat more tolerable in the made-for-TV version of this book. If I had to read this again, I think I'd KILL myself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6047617498914279357" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
